Q84 Part_A A sink in a directed graph is a vertex i such that there is an edge from every vertex j ≠ i to i and there is no edge from i to any other vertex. A directed graph G with n vertices is represented by its adjacency matrix A, where A[i] [j] = 1 if there is an edge directed from vertex i to j and 0 otherwise. The following algorithm determines whether there is a sink in the graph G. i = 0
do {
    j = i + 1;
    while ((j < n) && E1) 
       j++;
    if (j < n) E2;
} while (j < n);

flag = 1;
for (j = 0; j < n; j++)
    if ((j! = i) && E3)
        flag = 0;

if (flag)
    printf("Sink exists");
else
    printf ("Sink does not exist"); Choose the correct expressions for E 1 and E 2

